In [Part 1], we built the core foundations of our architectural overlay system. We established CoreOverlayConfig, the state-tracking CoreOverlayRef, and the abstract coordinator CoreOverlayService. However, foundations are only useful when you build upon them.
In Part 2, we are going to implement a concrete, fully-featured, and 100% type-safe Popup Overlay System. We will construct a reusable dynamic overlay wrapper, leverage CSS custom properties combined with Angular Signals for butter-smooth GPU-accelerated transition animations, and implement fully typed data-passing mechanics.
Best of all? We have completely purged the any type from our codebase.
The Concept: Structural Containers vs. Content
To keep our architecture highly decoupled, we split our popups into two pieces:

• The Container (PopupContainer): A reusable structural wrapper that handles animations, basic box shadows, accessibility roles (dialog vs alertdialog), backdrops, and close-on-escape events.

• The Content (Your Feature Component): Any standard Angular component you write. This component is completely unaware of how it is displayed; it simply asks for its inputs and triggers a close when done.
1. Typed Configuration & Tokens
When spawning a popup, we often need to pass inputs down to the dynamic component (DIALOG_DATA pattern) and receive typed outputs back. We start by extending our core configurations and setting up InjectionToken pairs:
import { InjectionToken } from '@angular/core';
import { ScrollStrategy } from '@angular/cdk/overlay';
import { CoreOverlayConfig } from './core-overlay-config';export type PopupRole = 'dialog' | 'alertdialog';
export class PopupConfig<D = unknown> extends CoreOverlayConfig {
role?: PopupRole = 'dialog';
data?: D | null = null;
ariaDescribedBy?: string | null = null;
ariaLabel?: string | null = null;
ariaModal?: boolean = false;
scrollStrategy?: ScrollStrategy;
}
export const POPUP_CONFIG = new InjectionToken<PopupConfig<unknown>>('POPUP_CONFIG');
export const POPUP_DATA = new InjectionToken<unknown>>('POPUP_DATA');
2. Refining the Custom Reference: PopupRef
To support keyboard accessibility (closing on ESCAPE) and mouse click interaction (backdrop closing), we implement PopupRef.
By inheriting from CoreOverlayRef, it naturally inherits the animation state signals. We also expose a fully typed componentInstance so callers can interact directly with the spawned class if necessary.
// popup-ref.ts
import { ComponentRef } from '@angular/core';
import { OverlayRef, GlobalPositionStrategy } from '@angular/cdk/overlay';
import { ESCAPE, hasModifierKey } from '@angular/cdk/keycodes';
import { filter, merge } from 'rxjs';
import { CoreOverlayRef } from './core-overlay-ref';
import { PopupConfig } from './popup-config';export type PopupPositions = { top?: string; bottom?: string; left?: string; right?: string; };
export class PopupRef<T, R = unknown, D = unknown> extends CoreOverlayRef<R, PopupConfig<D>> {
public componentInstance: T | null = null;
public componentRef: ComponentRef<T> | null = null;
constructor(overlayRef: OverlayRef, config: PopupConfig<D>) {
super(overlayRef, config);
const backdropClick = overlayRef.backdropClick();
const keyDowns = this.overlayRef.keydownEvents().pipe(
filter(event => event.keyCode === ESCAPE && !config.disableClose && !hasModifierKey(event))
);
merge(backdropClick, keyDowns).subscribe((event) => {
if (!config.disableClose) {
event.preventDefault();
this.close();
}
});
}
override close(result?: R): void {
super.close(result);
this.componentInstance = null;
this.componentRef = null;
}
updatePosition(position?: PopupPositions): this {
const strategy = this.overlayRef.getConfig().positionStrategy as GlobalPositionStrategy;
if (position && (position.left || position.right)) {
position.left ? strategy.left(position.left) : strategy.right(position.right);
} else {
strategy.centerHorizontally();
}
if (position && (position.top || position.bottom)) {
position.top ? strategy.top(position.top) : strategy.bottom(position.bottom);
} else {
strategy.centerVertically();
}
this.overlayRef.updatePosition();
return this;
}
}
3. The Animated Structural Shell: PopupContainer
This is where the magic happens. Instead of relying on heavy Angular @trigger animations which can be difficult to orchestrate across dynamically attached portals, we bind the state signals directly to host CSS classes.
We feed animation durations dynamically from TypeScript into CSS Variables (--popup-enter-duration), ensuring that CSS transition speeds always align with JS teardown timeouts!
import { ChangeDetectionStrategy, Component, inject, viewChild, ViewEncapsulation, ComponentRef } from '@angular/core';
import { CdkPortalOutlet, ComponentPortal } from '@angular/cdk/portal';
import { PopupRef } from './popup-ref';
import { POPUP_CONFIG } from './popup-config';@Component({
selector: 'app-popup-container',
standalone: true,
imports: [CdkPortalOutlet],
template: `
<div class="popup-panel">
<ng-template cdkPortalOutlet></ng-template>
</div>
`,
styleUrl: './popup-container.scss',
changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
encapsulation: ViewEncapsulation.None,
host: {
tabindex: '-1',
class: 'popup-host-wrapper',
'[attr.aria-modal]': '_config.ariaModal',
'[class.state-opening]': '_popupRef.isOpening()',
'[class.state-open]': '_popupRef.isOpen()',
'[class.state-closing]': '_popupRef.isClosing()',
'[class.state-closed]': '_popupRef.isClosed()',
'[id]': '_config.id',
'[attr.role]': '_config.role',
'[attr.aria-labelledby]': '_config.ariaLabel || null',
'[style.width]': "'100%'",
'[style.--popup-enter-duration]': '`${_popupRef.enterAnimationDuration}ms`',
'[style.--popup-exit-duration]': '`${_popupRef.exitAnimationDuration}ms`',
},
})
export class PopupContainer {
protected readonly _popupRef = inject(PopupRef<unknown, unknown, unknown>);
protected readonly _config = inject(POPUP_CONFIG);
private readonly _portalOutlet = viewChild.required(CdkPortalOutlet);
public attachComponentPortal<T>(portal: ComponentPortal<T>): ComponentRef<T> {
return this._portalOutlet().attach(portal);
}
}
// popup-container.scss
.popup-panel {
width: 100%;
opacity: 0;
transform: scale(0.85);
transition:
transform var(--popup-enter-duration, 300ms) cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1),
opacity var(--popup-enter-duration, 300ms) ease-out;
will-change: transform, opacity;
background: white;
border-radius: 12px;
box-shadow: 0 10px 25px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
}// Entrance States
.popup-host-wrapper.state-opening .popup-panel,
.popup-host-wrapper.state-open .popup-panel {
opacity: 1;
transform: scale(1);
}
// Exit States
.popup-host-wrapper.state-closing .popup-panel,
.popup-host-wrapper.state-closed .popup-panel {
opacity: 0;
transform: scale(0.85);
transition-duration: var(--popup-exit-duration, 150ms);
}
4. Implementing the Concrete PopupService
Now, we tie everything together. By subclassing CoreOverlayService, we implement the abstract _overlayConfigBuilder and expose a strictly-typed open() signature.
Notice how we safely map the custom providers array, providing the exact PopupRef instance and typed POPUP_DATA to the newly instantiated portal.
import { inject, Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { ComponentPortal, ComponentType } from '@angular/cdk/portal';
import { OverlayConfig } from '@angular/cdk/overlay';
import { _IdGenerator } from '@angular/cdk/a11y';
import { CoreOverlayService } from './core-overlay.service';
import { PopupRef } from './popup-ref';
import { PopupConfig, POPUP_CONFIG, POPUP_DATA } from './popup-config';
import { PopupContainer } from './popup-container.component';@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class PopupService extends CoreOverlayService<PopupRef<unknown, unknown, unknown>, PopupConfig<unknown>> {
private readonly _idGenerator = inject(_IdGenerator);
open<T, R = unknown, D = unknown>(component: ComponentType<T>,config?: PopupConfig<D>,): PopupRef<T, R, D> {
const _config = { ...new PopupConfig<D>(), ...config } as PopupConfig<D>;
_config.id = config?.id || this._idGenerator.getId('popup-');
const ref = this.openOverlay<R, T, PopupContainer, PopupConfig<D>>(component, {
container: PopupContainer,
config: _config,
createRef: (overlayRef, cfg) => new PopupRef<T, R, D>(overlayRef, cfg),
providers: (popupRef, cfg) => [
{ provide: PopupRef, useValue: popupRef },
{ provide: POPUP_CONFIG, useValue: cfg },
{ provide: POPUP_DATA, useValue: cfg.data },
],
attachContent: (containerRef, comp, cfg, popupRef) => {
const portal = new ComponentPortal(comp, cfg.viewContainerRef);
const contentRef = containerRef.instance.attachComponentPortal(portal);
popupRef.componentRef = contentRef;
popupRef.componentInstance = contentRef.instance;
},
});
return ref as unknown as PopupRef<T, R, D>;
}
protected override _overlayConfigBuilder(config: PopupConfig<unknown>): OverlayConfig {
return new OverlayConfig({
width: config.width,
height: config.height,
minWidth: config.minWidth,
hasBackdrop: config.hasBackdrop,
backdropClass: config.backdropClass || 'cdk-overlay-dark-backdrop',
panelClass: config.panelClass,
scrollStrategy: config.scrollStrategy ?? this._overlay.scrollStrategies.block(),
positionStrategy: this._overlay.position().global().centerVertically().centerHorizontally(),
});
}
}
How to use it in practice (Type-Safety Demo)
Let’s look at how beautiful the consumer experience is. Imagine you have a ConfirmPopup component that requires a specific data structure and returns a boolean state on close:
interface ConfirmData { title: string; body: string; }@Component({
template: `
<h3>{{ data.title }}</h3>
<p>{{ data.body }}</p>
<button (click)="ref.close(true)">Yes</button>
<button (click)="ref.close(false)">No</button>
`
})
export class ConfirmPopup {
protected readonly data = inject<ConfirmData>(POPUP_DATA);
protected readonly ref = inject<PopupRef<ConfirmPopup, boolean>>(PopupRef);
}
Inside your host page, you open it with complete compiler enforcement:
@Component({...})
export class DashboardComponent {
private readonly popupService = inject(PopupService); showConfirmation() {
const ref = this.popupService.open(ConfirmPopup, {
data: {
title: 'Are you sure?',
body: 'This action cannot be undone!'
}
});
ref.afterClosed().subscribe((didConfirm) => {
console.log('Result:', didConfirm);
});
}
}
Conclusion
We have completed our production-ready, highly-flexible, and fully type-safe Popup Overlay System! By extending our generic base:

• We created a dedicated, animated HTML wrapper shell.

• We encapsulated dynamic template elements (viewChild) inside their corresponding container classes.

• We mapped custom Angular Signals to synchronize hardware-accelerated CSS animations with JavaScript lifecycles.

• We eliminated all any usages to achieve absolute compile-time certainty.
In Part 3, we will expand on this architecture even further and implement a Drawer Slide-out (Bottom/Side Sheet) System that reuses the exact same core infrastructure under a different visual layout.
Stay tuned, and happy coding!
